The Time-of-Flight (ToF) Principle :
The Time-of-Flight (ToF) principle is the scientific foundation for distance measurement. It is the method of determining distance by measuring the time it takes for a signal (in this case, an ultrasonic sound pulse) to travel to a target and return to the sender.
Distance = velocity of sound wave * time 
The specific formula used in the project is:
Distance = (velocity of sound wave * time ) /2

•	Explanation of Division by Two: The measured time ($t_{\text{measured}}$) is the total time the pulse takes to travel from the sensor to the object and back to the sensor. Therefore, the actual one-way distance is calculated by using only half of the total measured time, which is mathematically achieved by dividing the full distance result by two.
